{"questionId":"35020825","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Let the function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced></math> represent the volume of the block of sugar, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>mm</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> seconds after it is placed in hot coffee. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced></math> is given by</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>60</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>008</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>, for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>50</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>State one reason why the side length of the cube may not always decrease at a constant rate.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>decreasing/change in coffee temperature&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>R1</em></strong></p>\n<p>decreasing/change in surface area of the cube</p>\n<p>the cube breaks apart into smaller pieces</p>\n<p>dissolution rate related to volume of the cube</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>R1</strong></em> for a reasonable explanation of a change in rate.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"35020825","referenceCode":"24M.1.SL.TZ1.9d","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"State one reason why the side length of the cube may not always decrease at a constant rate.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"d","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry an